author: 八雲よみ /Yakumo Yomi
text:
It shouldn't be that difficult to pick up the basics. I'm nowhere near fluent, but I do have knowledge of the language (I can read hiragana, katakana, some kanji, and know grammar/sentence structure). The biggest barrier is probably going to be vocabulary. Since the Hololive streamers are native speakers, they use a lot of slang/informal language that you probably won't learn from a textbook/learning app.

That said, definitely see if you can learn the basics. Just memorizing hiragana and katakana shouldn't take you too long, and you'll likely learn the basics of grammar along the way.

author: Danny Leonardi
text:
@PastelSumi  you can start from learning basic hiragana and katakana. this alone can get you quite far when reading simple sentences. then, you can start learning vocabularies and tenses that are almost always used in everyday conversation. for this, I do think you need some sort of guidance (e.g. book for learning japanese)

For example: the text in 11:14 reads "ayame-chan no tokui ryouri wa nandesuka? mata, saikin hamatteiru tabemono wa arimasuka?" If I separate it:
 
Ayame-chan (hiragana of her name, Ayame)
no (can be translated to suffix 's to indicate posession)
tokui (得意, meaning "strong point" or "one's specialty")
ryouri (料理, meaning "cooking" or "dish")
wa (it's using "ha" hiragana (は), but is read as "wa" in grammatical context. it's equivalent to "is" or "are" in english)
nandesuka? (meaning "what". the core verb is "nani" (何), can also be read as "nan". the "desuka" is added for formal sentences. If you're talking to a friend, you can technically ask "what" question with "nani")

Mata, (also,)
saikin (最近, meaning "recently")
hamatteiru (the -ing verb form of "hamaru", which roughly means "to be addicted to, to be crazy about", or simply "to really like". verbs in japanese can be turned into continuous form by changing the suffix -ru to -tteiru, so from "hamaru" to "hamatteiru", to indicate that the question refers to what they're really into right now)
tabemono (食べ物, meaning "food", which comes from tabe(ru) (食べ(る), meaning "eat"), and mono (物, meaning "thing/object"))
wa (same as above)
arimasuka (roughly translates to "is there?". it comes from the term "arimasu" (or simply "aru" in non-formal term) which is used to indicate if something exists or not (like "there is/there are"). if added with ka in the end, it turns into question form)

So, combined and rearranged, it can be translated as "What is Ayame-chan's specialty dish? Also, is there any food that (Ayame-chan) really like recently?"

(I have learned Japanese in college for work purposes, but I don't really have the chance to translate sentences into English, so feel free if anyone wants to correct me)
